“it is seldom necessary for a trained man to shoot a bird to know, at the specific level, precisely what it is”). This idea was opposed by Allan Phillips, who published several articles and books about Arizona birds. He refused to recognize Knorr's marks in that state and claimed in private correspondence that "there are so many all-black swifts that you can't
                                 
 be able to prove which one you saw in Arizona "(eng. "there are a great many all-black swifts, and you have not really proved which one is in Arizona").